text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy Lessons from PLAY%0a%0a:Author: AnanyaV%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aPolysemy of the word "play"%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhen you are young, you PLAY outside with your friends, and PLAY pranks on them. You also PLAY board games like Monopoly, and you might not always PLAY fair or PLAY by the rules. When you take part in a sport, you PLAY that sport, and in competitive sports, you PLAY against teams. In the theater, you watch a PLAY, where actors PLAY characters. If you like music, you might PLAY music on your phone, or you might learn to PLAY an instrument. When you are in a stressful situation, you try to PLAY it cool, and if you are running out of time, you might PLAY for time. Sometimes, you avoid risks and PLAY it safe. If you want to make something happen, you bring it into PLAY.%0a%0aIn the language of the Nacirema, “play” is often attributed to areas that the Nacirema people view as leisurely, being used within the contexts of games, music, sports, and theatre. However, there are some exceptions to this as we have seen in the latter examples, with “play” being used to describe how one might react to a situation. These contextual differences in the use of “play” showcase the linguistic peculiarities of the Nacirema culture.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210328-012109-600570#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Deeper linguistic analysis of the Nacireman people  %0a-> - AlbertL%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI commend Ananya for her excellent contributions here to our understanding of the "play" in the Nacireman language. However, I believe there is far deeper meaning to be extracted beyond the the simple polysemy of the word. "Play" evokes the idyllic activities and games of youth yet in a surprising turn, the Nacireman people use it not only for these activities, but also for all manners of stressful and dark situations. Ananya points out several examples such as playing it cool, playing for time, and playing it safe. This shows that the Nacireman are a light-hearted people who's worldview revolve around not taking life or their problems too seriously. Instead when the Namerican people bump into stress, they simply remind themselves of their idyllic youth to make their worries go away. We can see the same philosophy in another one of their sayings. "It means no worries, fr the rest of your days. It's our problem-free philosophy, Hakuna Matata!" This is a famous line of a story told to the children in Nacirema and you would be hard pressed to find one who did not know the phrase. The use of play is but another reflection of this Hakuna Matata.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210328-012109-600570#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)
